rce code. \r\n\r\nFirstly, you should google it and type `tig git` in the search bar, then click the second matched item to the homepage of tig. \r\n\r\nSecondly, find the line `Git URL: git://repo.or.cz/tig.git` below the `Resources` heading.\r\n\r\nThirdly, launch your terminal, run the following command:\r\n\r\n    git clone git://repo.or.cz/tig.git\r\n\r\nThe prerequisite is __Git__ had been installed in your system.',19,'2011-07-16 08:22:27','2011-07-16 13:17:04',3),(56,'good!\r\n',20,'2011-07-17 07:43:18','2011-07-17 07:43:18',2),(57,'**Thanks very much.\r\nEven through it takes some time to get it down. I found there are about 8000 lines about the text. I\'m afraid I may have some trouble reading and modifying it. do you have some useful advices.\r\n**Thanks again.',19,'2011-07-17 08:12:14','2011-07-17 08:12:14',2),(58,'It\'s my pleasure to help you! Exactly, there are several thousand lines code in one file, really big file to a novice. You may fell confused and bored. It\'s always difficult at the beginning. Don\'t worry, with the help of __Git__, which will make our coding life easy.\r\n\r\nNow you have gotten the tig repository, and see a number of files in the tig directory. Since tig uses git to manage its codebase, what you have seen is the content of the latest commit, so the source file is hard to read. How can you get a small source file? Let\'s say we want to view the initial commit content, which must contain a few lines code. To do this, run the command below in your terminal. It looks like this:\r\n   \r\n    git checkout -q commit\r\n\r\nNote if you omit \"-q\" option, you can get much message. You must use a specified commit to substitute \"commit\", such as 800a900c that is the first commit.\r\n\r\nAssuming everything goes well, run __ls__ command. I bet you will feel strange. There is only a couple of files, and other files are gone (actually not). You just go back to previous commit version. Now you can play with the source file easily.\r\n